    {\displaystyle B_{\mathrm {new} }=(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{n}),}
   one has that 
  
    
      
        
          B
          
            
              n
              e
              w
            
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle B_{\mathrm {new} }}
   is a basis of V if and only if the matrix A is invertible, or equivalently if it has a nonzero determinant. In this case, A is said to be the change-of-basis matrix from the basis 
  
    
      
        
          B
          
            
              o
              l
              d
            
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle B_{\mathrm {old} }}
   to the basis 
  
    
      
        
          B
          
            
              n
              e
              w
            
          
        
        .
      
    
    {\displaystyle B_{\mathrm {new} }.}
  
Given a vector 
  
    
      
